    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <!-- Back to Home Button -->
    <div class="back-button-container">
        <button class="back-button" onclick="goBackHome()">&#8592; Back to Parameters</button>
    </div>

    <div class="container">
        <h1>Oxidation-Reduction Potential (ORP) Measurement</h1>
        
        <div class="definition-box">
            <div class="definition-title">ORP (Oxidation-Reduction Potential)</div>
            <p>A measurement of a solution's ability to oxidize or reduce substances, expressed in millivolts (mV). Positive values indicate oxidizing conditions, while negative values indicate reducing conditions.</p>
        </div>

        <p>ORP is a critical parameter for assessing water quality, disinfection effectiveness, and chemical processes in aquatic environments.</p>

        <button class="btn" onclick="toggleInfo()">Show Measurement Details</button>
        
        <div class="info-section" id="moreInfo" style="display: none;">
            <h2>Fundamentals of ORP</h2>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li><span class="highlight">Electron transfer:</span> ORP measures the tendency of a chemical species to acquire electrons (reduction) or lose electrons (oxidation)</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Measurement scale:</span> Ranges from -2000 mV (strong reducing) to +2000 mV (strong oxidizing)</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Standard hydrogen electrode (SHE):</span> Reference point (0 mV) for all ORP measurements</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Nernst equation:</span> <div class="formula">E = EÂ° - (RT/nF)lnQ</div> describes the relationship between ORP and chemical activity</li>
            </ul>

            <img src="images/orp-sensor.jpg" alt="ORP measurement sensor" class="sensor-image">

            <h2>Measurement Technology</h2>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li><span class="highlight">ORP electrodes:</span> Consist of a platinum or gold measuring electrode and a reference electrode</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Working principle:</span> Measures voltage difference generated by electron transfer reactions</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Calibration:</span> Typically performed using Zobell's solution (+228 mV) or Light's solution (+468 mV)</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Maintenance:</span> Requires regular cleaning and storage in proper solution</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Key Applications</h2>
            <div class="application-card">
                <div class="application-title">Water Treatment</div>
                <ul>
                    <li>Monitoring chlorine disinfection (600-800 mV ideal for drinking water)</li>
                    <li>Ozone treatment control</li>
                    <li>Swimming pool and spa sanitation</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="application-card">
                <div class="application-title">Environmental Monitoring</div>
                <ul>
                    <li>Assessing redox conditions in natural waters</li>
                    <li>Detecting anoxic conditions in lakes and reservoirs</li>
                    <li>Monitoring groundwater contamination</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="application-card">
                <div class="application-title">Industrial Processes</div>
                <ul>
                    <li>Wastewater treatment process control</li>
                    <li>Cooling water system monitoring</li>
                    <li>Chemical manufacturing processes</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h2>Interpretation of ORP Values</h2>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li><span class="highlight">> +400 mV:</span> Oxidizing conditions (presence of oxygen, chlorine, ozone)</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">+100 to +400 mV:</span> Aerobic conditions</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">-100 to +100 mV:</span> Transitional (mixed aerobic/anaerobic)</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">< -100 mV:</span> Reducing conditions (presence of sulfides, organic matter)</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Factors Affecting ORP</h2>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li><span class="highlight">pH:</span> ORP decreases by approximately 59 mV for each pH unit increase</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Temperature:</span> Affects reaction kinetics and electrode response</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Dissolved oxygen:</span> Major contributor to oxidizing potential</li>
                <li><span class="highlight">Chemical contaminants:</span> Reducing agents like HâS lower ORP</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        function goBackHome() {
            window.location.href = 'parameters';
        }

        function toggleInfo() {
            const info = document.getElementById("moreInfo");
            const button = document.querySelector(".btn");
            
            if (info.style.display === "none") {
                info.style.display = "block";
                button.textContent = "Hide Measurement Details";
            } else {
                info.style.display = "none";
                button.textContent = "Show Measurement Details";
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
